Exercise 1 — RAII for File Handling

Problem:
Write a class FileRAII that opens a file in its constructor and closes it in the destructor. Throw an exception if the file cannot be opened.

#include <fstream>
#include <string>

class FileRAII {
    std::ifstream file;
public:
    FileRAII(const std::string& filename); // open file
    ~FileRAII();                            // close file automatically
    void readLine();                        // read a line
};

Tasks:

Implement constructor to open the file.
Throw std::runtime_error if file cannot be opened.
Implement destructor to close the file automatically.
Write main() to test stack unwinding by throwing an exception after opening the file.

Hint:

Use file.is_open() to check if the file opened successfully.
Ensure destructor never throws.
Exercise 2 — Custom Smart Pointer

Problem:
Create a simple smart pointer class SimplePtr<T> that manages a dynamically allocated object and deletes it automatically.

template <typename T>
class SimplePtr {
    T* ptr;
public:
    explicit SimplePtr(T* p = nullptr); // constructor
    ~SimplePtr();                        // destructor deletes ptr
    T& operator*();                      // dereference operator
    T* operator->();                     // arrow operator
};

Tasks:

Implement constructor to store pointer.
Implement destructor to free memory.
Implement dereference and arrow operators.
Test exception safety by throwing an exception after creating a SimplePtr object — memory should be freed automatically.

Hint:

Use delete ptr in destructor.
Stack unwinding ensures proper cleanup.
Exercise 3 — Exception Safety Guarantee

Problem:
Implement a function addElementSafe(std::vector<int>& v, int x) that provides strong exception safety: either the element is added or the vector remains unchanged if an exception occurs.

#include <vector>

void addElementSafe(std::vector<int>& v, int x);

Tasks:

Use a temporary vector to perform the operation.
Commit changes only after the operation succeeds.
Throw an exception artificially to test strong guarantee.

Hint:

Copy vector → modify → assign back.
Exercise 4 — Virtual Destructor

Problem:
Create a base class Shape and derived class Circle. Use dynamic allocation. Ensure deleting a Shape* pointing to a Circle calls both destructors.

class Shape {
public:
    virtual ~Shape(); // make virtual
};

class Circle : public Shape {
public:
    ~Circle();
};

Tasks:

Print a message in each destructor.
Allocate Shape* s = new Circle();
Delete s and check output.

Expected Behavior:

Circle destructor runs first
Then Shape destructor

Hint:

Without virtual, only base destructor runs → resource leak.
Exercise 5 — Mutex + RAII (Thread Safety)

Problem:
Write a function that updates a shared integer using a std::mutex and ensures the mutex is released even if an exception occurs.

#include <mutex>

std::mutex m;
int sharedValue = 0;

void safeUpdate(int x);

Tasks:

Use std::lock_guard<std::mutex> to manage mutex.
Throw an exception artificially after locking.
Ensure mutex is released automatically.

Hint:

RAII with lock_guard guarantees unlock on stack unwinding.
